{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17588281","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17588281"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T09:05:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T09:05:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15123"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15123","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15123"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7811"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66748"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7811","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7811"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15123"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52202"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"},{"type":"tags","id":"8134"},{"type":"tags","id":"10000"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19045"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19046"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21490"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66748","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66748"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EGastro-oesophageal reflux disease (GORD) is a common condition affecting the upper gastrointestinal tract.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following correctly describes the pathophysiology of this condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Decreased gastric volume","Decreased intra-abdominal pressure","Decreased lower oesophageal sphincter tone","Increased frequency of transient lower oesophageal sphincter relaxations","Impaired secondary peristalsis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGORD occurs primarily due to \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreased frequency of transient lower oesophageal sphincter relaxations\u003C/strong\u003E. These are inappropriate relaxations not triggered by swallowing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe anti-reflux barrier requires adequate \u003Cstrong\u003Eintra-abdominal pressure\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Egastric volume\u003C/strong\u003E - decreases in these factors do not cause GORD. \u003Cstrong\u003ELower oesophageal sphincter tone\u003C/strong\u003E may be reduced in some cases but is not the primary mechanism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESecondary peristalsis\u003C/strong\u003E is actually increased in GORD as a protective mechanism to clear refluxed material from the oesophagus. This is accompanied by increased saliva production to neutralise acid.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Gastro-oesophageal reflux disease occurs due to dysfunction of the lower oesophageal sphincter with inappropriate transient relaxations.","The anti-reflux barrier depends on adequate intra-abdominal pressure and stomach volume.","Primary and secondary peristalsis help clear refluxed material from the oesophagus."],"references":["Dent J, El-Serag HB, Wallander MA, Johansson S. Epidemiology of gastro-oesophageal reflux disease: a systematic review. Gut. 2005 May;54(5):710-7. doi: 10.1136/gut.2004.051821. PMID: 15831922; PMCID: PMC1774487.","Tack J, Pandolfino JE. Pathophysiology of Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease. Gastroenterology. 2018 Jan;154(2):277-288. doi: 10.1053/j.gastro.2017.09.047. Epub 2017 Oct 14. PMID: 29037470.","Herregods TV, Bredenoord AJ, Smout AJ. Pathophysiology of gastroesophageal reflux disease: new understanding in a new era. Neurogastroenterol Motil. 2015 Sep;27(9):1202-13. doi: 10.1111/nmo.12611. Epub 2015 Jun 5. PMID: 26053301.","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52202"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15123"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52202","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52202"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-01T21:04:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-01T21:04:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7811"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66748"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4928"},